									<StackPanel
										Margin="2,2,5,2">
										<TextBlock
											FontWeight="Bold">What is a community server?</TextBlock>
										<TextBlock
											TextWrapping="Wrap">An Athena Community Server (ACS) allows users to share ink in real time. Setting up a server is easy. It's just small program and a port forward entry in your firewall(s) but it gives your community an amazing tool that helps to foster better coordination and communication.</TextBlock>
										<TextBlock
											TextWrapping="Wrap"
											Margin="0,10,0,0">When users connect to a community server, they can create 'Rooms'. When you're in a room, you can see the ink that 'active' users in your room draw. You can join multiple rooms and 'monitor' the ink that is drawn in them but you can only ever be 'active' in a single room and the participants in that room are the ones with whom your ink will be shared.</TextBlock>
										<TextBlock
											TextWrapping="Wrap"
											Margin="0,10,0,0">That presents your community with a powerful coordination tool. And because it runs as a separate server, it's available even when you're not playing ARMA. Having this experience outside of ARMA is great for collaborting on mission designs, discussing mission plans and execution strategies or for training purposes in Tactical Decision Training or 'What If' type scenarios.</TextBlock>
										<TextBlock
											TextWrapping="Wrap"
											Margin="0,10,0,0">When you're in game, various departments and groups within your structure can have their own rooms in which they are 'active' in but which other players monitor. A Platoon lead can devise a strategy that Squad leads 'monitor' and so on and so on down the chain of command. This kind of flexibility comes in handy especially for JTAC scenarios in which a community member has to coordinate with various other elements.</TextBlock>
										<TextBlock
											TextWrapping="Wrap"
											Margin="0,10,0,0">If your community can benefit from an ACS and you would like more information, please visit the AthenaMod.com website.</TextBlock>
